    "summary": "B — Afterword, not Preface; interpretive not orienting",
    "content": "**B — Translator's Afterword.**\n\nThree reasons:\n\n1. **It is interpretive, not orienting.** The Preface orients; the Afterword interprets. The poet/Dichter distinction is a cross-traditional connection that enriches the reader's understanding *after* they have encountered the passage themselves. Putting it in the Preface would pre-frame the Appendix's closing gesture before the reader reaches it.\n\n2. **The passage is itself a culmination.** The \"我们正是这样的创造者\" sentence comes at the end of the Appendix -- it is the collection's final rhetorical and philosophical move, the moment where the framework returns to everyday life. The reader should arrive at this sentence with their own experiential accumulation from all eight essays, not with a Heidegger comparison already loaded. The Afterword is the right place to say: \"Now that you have read that sentence, here is what makes it distinctive.\"\n\n3. **It fits perfectly in Afterword Section B (Cross-Traditional Connections), under the Existentialist heading.** The existentialism-expert's five-point contrast is exactly the kind of scholarly positioning the Afterword was designed for. It belongs alongside the Camus/Nietzsche/Heidegger comparisons already planned for that section. The shift from \"How do I become authentic?\" to \"How do I notice that I already am?\" is a genuinely illuminating framing -- but it is illuminating precisely because the reader has already experienced the collection's progression from metaphysics through nihilism to the poetic, and can now recognize the contrast from their own reading.\n\nFrom my domain specifically: the universality point (everyone is a poet, not a rare figure) also resonates with Wittgenstein's insistence that philosophy is not a specialized activity but an attempt to see clearly what is already before us (PI section 129: \"The aspects of things that are most important for us are hidden because of their simplicity and familiarity\"). The author's poet is someone who notices what they are already doing -- which is precisely the Wittgensteinian therapeutic move. This connection strengthens the Afterword's Wittgenstein section as well."
  }
}
